  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal crime in the United States, and the penalties for violating money laundering laws can be severe. Under federal law, specifically the **Money Laundering Control Act** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957), the penalties depend on the specific offense and the amount of money involved. Key penalties include:\n\n1. **Criminal Penalties**:\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: Violations can result in:\n     - Up to **20 years** in federal prison.\n     - Fines of up to **$500,000** or **twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: Engaging in monetary transactions involving criminally derived property ($10,000 or more) can result in:\n     - Up to **10 years** in prison.\n     - Fines of up to **$250,000** or **twice the value of the property**.\n\n2. **Civil Penalties**:\n   - Civil forfeiture of assets involved in or derived from money laundering.\n   - Additional fines may be imposed by regulatory agencies, such as the **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)**.\n\n3. **Enhanced Penalties**:\n   - If the money laundering is connected to **drug trafficking**, **terrorism**, or other serious crimes, penalties can be more severe, including longer prison sentences.\n   - Repeat offenders may face harsher penalties.\n\n4. **Additional Consequences**:\n   - Conviction for money laundering can result in the loss of professional licenses (e.g., banking, legal, or financial services).\n   - Individuals may face difficulties in obtaining future employment or credit.\n\n5. **International Money Laundering**:\n   - Money laundering involving international transactions can trigger additional charges under laws like the **Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA)** or **USA PATRIOT Act**, leading to further penalties.\n\nFederal prosecutors often pursue money laundering charges alongside other offenses, such as fraud, racketeering, or drug trafficking, which can compound the penalties. Legal representation is crucial for individuals accused of money laundering, as the consequences can be life-altering.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
